Question 1

Question: Are there differences in loan default rates by loan purpose?

Answer: Yes, the data indicates that credit card and medical loans have significantly larger default rates than any other type of loan. In fact, both of these loan types have default rates at more than 50%. This is nearly two times the average default rate for all other loan types.

Question 2

Question: Is there is a relationship between loan amount and loan default status?

Answer: Yes there is a relationship between loan amount and loan default status. To answer this question, we have created a average loan amount summary table and conducted a t-test. We have also created a boxplot to check the loan default status by loan amount. The plot shows the individuals with higher loan amounts have higher chances of being of default as compare to low amount customers. The descriptive summary shows the individuals who are defaulted have higher average loan amounts as compare to non-default customers. The t-test is significant with p-value less than 0.0001 indicating loan amount is associated with the loan default.

loans_df %>%
  group_by(loan_default) %>%
  reframe(customers = n(), average_loan_amount = mean(loan_amount)) %>% knitr::kable()
loan_default customers average_loan_amount
yes 1530 17447.53
no 2580 16245.21 
t.test(loan_amount ~ loan_default, data = loans_df)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  loan_amount by loan_default
## t = 3.803, df = 3440.2, p-value = 0.0001455
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group yes and group no is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   582.4527 1822.1863
## sample estimates:
## mean in group yes  mean in group no 
##          17447.53          16245.21
ggplot(loans_df, aes(x = loan_default, y = loan_amount, fill = loan_default))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(x = 'Loan Default Status', y = 'Loan Amount', fill = 'Default Status', 
       title = 'Loan default Status by Loan Amount')+
  theme_light()

Question 3

Question: How the interest rate is associated with the loan default?

Answer: To answer this question, we have create a descriptive summary table, conducted a t-test and visualized a histogram by default status. The descriptive summary shows the customers who defaulted have average interest rate of 14.89% while the non-default customers have lower interest rate of 9.3%. The histogram of interest rate by loan default status shows the individuals who defaulted have higher range of interest rates as compare to the non-default customers. The interest rate range of non-default customer is between 5-15 while the interest rate range of defaulted range between 10 to 20. The t test is significant indicating interest rate is associated with loan default.

In this section of the project, you will fit three classification algorithms to predict the response variable,loan_default. You should use all of the other variables in the loans_df data as predictor variables for each model.

You must follow the machine learning steps below.

The data splitting and feature engineering steps should only be done once so that your models are using the same data and feature engineering steps for training.

  • Split the loans_df data into a training and test set (remember to set your seed)
  • Specify a feature engineering pipeline with the recipes package
    • You can include steps such as skewness transformation, dummy variable encoding or any other steps you find appropriate
  • Specify a parsnip model object
    • You may choose from the following classification algorithms:
      • Logistic Regression
      • LDA
      • QDA
      • KNN
      • Decision Tree
      • Random Forest
  • Package your recipe and model into a workflow
  • Fit your workflow to the training data
    • If your model has hyperparameters:
      • Split the training data into 5 folds for 5-fold cross validation using vfold_cv (remember to set your seed)
      • Perform hyperparamter tuning with a random grid search using the grid_random() function
      • Hyperparameter tuning can take a significant amount of computing time. Be careful not to set the size argument of grid_random() too large. I recommend size = 10 or smaller.
      • Select the best model with select_best() and finalize your workflow
  • Evaluate model performance on the test set by plotting an ROC curve using autoplot() and calculating the area under the ROC curve on your test data

tree_model <- decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune(), 
                            tree_depth = tune(),min_n = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("rpart") %>%
  set_mode("classification")

tree_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(loan_recipe) %>%
  add_model(tree_model)


tree_grid <- grid_regular(
  cost_complexity(range = c(-5, -1)), 
  tree_depth(range = c(1, 10)),       
  min_n(range = c(5, 50)),             
  levels = 5                          
)

set.seed(123)
tree_tune_results <- tune_grid(
  tree_workflow,
  resamples = cv_folds,
  grid = tree_grid,
  metrics = metric_set(roc_auc) 
)

best_tree <- select_best(tree_tune_results, metric = "roc_auc")
final_tree <- finalize_model(tree_model, best_tree)

tree_final <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(loan_recipe) %>%
  add_model(final_tree) %>%
  last_fit(data_split)

tree_results <- tree_final %>% collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric %in% c('accuracy', 'roc_auc')) %>%
  data.frame(Model = c('Decision Tree', 'Decision Tree')) %>%
  select(Model, .metric, .estimate)
tree_results

Model 3

rf_model <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(), trees = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("randomForest") %>%
  set_mode("classification")


rf_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(loan_recipe) %>%
  add_model(rf_model)


rf_grid <- grid_random(mtry(range = c(1, 10)), trees(range = c(50, 500)), size = 10)

set.seed(123)
rf_tune <- tune_grid(
  rf_workflow,
  resamples = cv_folds,
  grid = rf_grid,
  control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE)

final_rf <- finalize_model(rf_model, best_rf)

rf_final <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(loan_recipe) %>%
  add_model(final_rf) %>%
  last_fit(data_split)

rf_results <- rf_final %>% collect_metrics() %>%

Summary of Results [50 Points]

Write a summary of your overall findings and recommendations to the executives at the bank. Think of this section as your closing remarks of a presentation, where you summarize your key findings, model performance, and make recommendations to improve loan processes at the bank.

Your executive summary must be written in a business tone, with minimal grammatical errors, and should include the following sections:

1. Introduction

In this project, our objective is to help a national bank address a pressing business challenge: identifying and mitigating the risk of loan defaults. The dataset used, loans_df, contains detailed information on over 4,000 personal loan customers from the Middle Atlantic and Northeast regions who secured loans in 2017. With increasing rates of loan default in recent years, the bank has been facing significant financial losses, prompting an urgent need to better understand the factors associated with loan default and to identify customers at risk of defaulting. Loan defaults can erode a bank’s profitability, affect cash flow stability, and lead to higher costs in managing non-performing assets. The goal of this analysis is determine the factors such as loan characteristics, borrower financial metrics, or credit history, are most strongly associated with default and to develop machine learning models to predict whether a customer will default on their loan. Evaluating the accuracy of these models will help us assess their reliability in real-world applications. By predicting the likelihood of default, the bank can more effectively prioritize high-risk cases and implement targeted risk management strategies.

2. Explanatory Data Analysis

The exploratory data analysis highlights several critical insights into loan default risk, emphasizing key borrower characteristics that are essential for the bank’s risk assessment and loan management strategies. Firstly, loans for credit card and medical expenses exhibit default rates exceeding 50%, nearly double the average for other loan types. This suggests these categories are inherently riskier, signaling a need for closer scrutiny or modified lending criteria in these areas. Additionally, the analysis reveals a strong correlation between higher loan amounts and increased default rates, as well as a significant association between elevated interest rates (averaging nearly 15% for defaulters) and default status. These findings imply that loan terms, particularly interest rates, may be crucial factors in managing default risk. Furthermore, the analysis shows that customers with lower annual incomes are more likely to default, with an average income difference of over $8,000 between defaulters and non-defaulters, highlighting income as a potential determinant of repayment capability. Lastly, homeownership status emerged as an important variable; renters and those with mortgages show significantly higher default rates than homeowners, indicating that stable housing ownership may reflect financial stability. These insights lay a strong foundation for targeted recommendations to improve risk mitigation, optimize loan approval processes, and ultimately enhance the bank’s financial resilience.

3. Best Classification Model

The random forest model emerged as the best choice for predicting loan defaults. This model achieved an accuracy of approximately 90% on the test data, which suggests it correctly identifies defaults and non-defaults 90% of the time. Moreover, it resulted highest ROC AUC score of 0.97. The ROC AUC score is especially informative because it ranges from 0 to 1, with a score near 1 signifying near-perfect distinction. In our case, a score of 0.97 implies that the model is very effective at separating high-risk customers from low-risk ones. When visualized, the Random Forest ROC curve is closer to the top-left corner, indicating strong performance. By comparison, the Decision Tree model’s ROC curve was close but slightly lower, and KNN’s curve was noticeably lower, showing it to be the least accurate model for this dataset. For the bank, this means that using the Random Forest model could significantly reduce the risk of lending to high-risk customers while maintaining a high level of accuracy in identifying those who are safe to lend to. This level of accuracy is vital for minimizing defaults, ensuring financial stability, and making more informed lending decisions.

4. Recommendation

Our analysis revealed that customers with credit card and medical loans have significantly higher default rates, with defaults exceeding 50% for these categories. Implementing higher interest rates, additional security, or lower borrowing limits on these loan types could mitigate risks. Additionally, customers with lower annual incomes and those who live in rented or mortgaged homes have higher default probabilities, indicating that income stability and homeownership are important factors in loan repayment. The bank should consider adjusting loan eligibility requirements, such as setting minimum income thresholds or requiring higher credit scores for high-risk loan purposes.

5. Conclusion

In this analysis, we explored the factors associated with loan default among customers to help the bank better understand the characteristics and conditions linked to default risk. Through exploratory data analysis, we found notable trends: credit card and medical loans exhibited particularly high default rates, and customers with lower annual incomes, higher loan amounts, or higher interest rates were also more likely to default. Additionally, those who rent or have mortgages showed higher default likelihood compared to homeowners, suggesting that financial stability plays a significant role in loan repayment.

To address these insights, we implemented and evaluated three machine learning models—KNN, decision trees, and random forests—to predict loan default. Among these, the random forest model performed best, achieving a high accuracy and AUC-ROC score, indicating its strong predictive power. This model enables the bank to accurately identify high-risk customers, potentially allowing for proactive risk mitigation.

set.seed(123)
data_split <- initial_split(loans_df, prop = 0.7, strata = 'loan_default')
train_data <- training(data_split)
test_data <- testing(data_split)


loan_recipe <- recipe(loan_default ~ ., data = train_data) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_corr(all_numeric_predictors(), threshold = 0.80) %>%
  step_YeoJohnson(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes())


knn_model <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("kknn") %>%
  set_mode("classification")


knn_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(loan_recipe) %>%
  add_model(knn_model)


set.seed(123)
cv_folds <- vfold_cv(train_data, v = 5)

knn_grid <- grid_regular(neighbors(range = c(1, 20)), levels = 10)


set.seed(123)
knn_tune <- tune_grid(
  knn_workflow,
  resamples = cv_folds,
  grid = knn_grid,
  control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE)
)

best_knn <- select_best(knn_tune, metric = "roc_auc")


final_knn <- finalize_model(knn_model, best_knn)

knn_final <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(loan_recipe) %>%
  add_model(final_knn) %>%
  last_fit(data_split)

knn_results <- knn_final %>% collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric %in% c('accuracy', 'roc_auc')) %>%
  data.frame(Model = c('KNN', 'KNN')) %>%
  select(Model, .metric, .estimate)

  select(Model, .metric, .estimate)
rf_results

knn_results %>% rbind(tree_results, rf_results) %>%
  arrange(desc(.estimate)) %>% knitr::kable()

knn_auc <- knn_final %>%
  collect_predictions() %>% 
  roc_curve(loan_default, .pred_yes) %>% 
  mutate(model = "KNN")

tree_auc <- tree_final %>%
  collect_predictions() %>% 
  roc_curve(loan_default, .pred_yes) %>% 
  mutate(model = "Decision Tree")

rf_auc <- rf_final %>%
  collect_predictions() %>% 
  roc_curve(loan_default, .pred_yes) %>% 
  mutate(model = "Random Forest")


bind_rows(knn_auc, tree_auc, rf_auc) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = 1 - specificity, y = sensitivity, col = model)) + 
  geom_path(lwd = 1.5, alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_abline(lty = 3) + 
  coord_equal() +
  theme_light()+
  ggtitle('ROC plot of the models on test data')
